<TITLE> 57 convicted, 5 acquitted in Feni BDR verdict </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Feni, April 18 (bdnews24.com)  A special BDR court in Feni has convicted 57 out of 62 riflesmen for the offence of committing rebellion. Four border guards - Habildar Ruhul Amin, Sepoy Md. Mizanur Rahman, Sepoy Md. Basir Ahmed and Sepoy Mohiuddin Rony - were given the maximum penalty of seven years imprisonment. Outgoing BDR director general Maj Gen Mainul Islam, who headed the panel of judges, delivered the verdict on Sunday. The accused were charged with rebelling in support of their comrades in Pilkhana, Dhaka where the rebellion of Feb 25-26, 2009 saw about 70 people dead, including 57 army officers deputed to the BDR. It was alleged that a contingent of Feni border guards took up arms, fired in public and blocked the Feni-Maizdi Road on Feb 26. Nyek Emranul Haque Bhuya, Nyek Osman Haider and Sepoy driver Md. Abu Hanifa were sentenced for four and half years in jail and Nyek Md. Moklesur Rahman was sentenced to four years and three months. The remaining men were sentenced to terms of imprisonment from 4 months to 4 years. Most of them were also fined Tk 100 each other  the highest level of fine that the court can impose. The five acquitted men were Habilder Muhammad Ali, Nyek Md. Dulal Mia, Lance Nyek Signal Md. Saiful Islam, Sepoy Kazi Saifuzzaman and Sepoy Md. Omar Raruk. When the verdict was read out, the accused started to express their discontent loudly, and relatives of the BDR men who came to hear the verdict started crying Most of the accused have already spent over one year in prison. Earlier the 62 accused BDR men were brought to the court ion the morning under tight security. Deputy attorney general advocate Md. Forhad Ahmad, special prosecutor advocate Mosarraf Hossain Kajol, ad. Dewan Mohi Uddin, Lt. Col. Akhteruzzaman, Maj. Md. Maksudul Alam was present in the court to assist proceedings. Six special courts, including two in Dhaka, are trying some 3,500 border guards accused in some 40 cases around the country. The Feni verdict is the third set of verdicts to be returned. Earlier, on April 7, a special court in Panchagar sentenced all 29 of the accused for different terms of imprisonment. On April 11 in Thakurgaon, 50 riflesmen were convicted and one acquitted. bdn
